shared_text:
BEAM
August 12 at 6:08 PM ·

An #UnplannedOutage occurred this morning after a Russell County tractor mowing the right of way destroyed the main fiber cable pedestal providing service to the areas of Seale, Hurtsboro, and Hatchechubbee as well as Russell County schools.

As of 5:32p EST, ALL subscriber's services were restored! If your internet services have not restored, please power cycle the modem to reconnect (If you're unable to connect, please call us at 334-298-7000).

Our technicians definitely prevailed and worked so very hard to get the services restored as quickly as possible beating the expectations to take overnight to fix.

We apologize for the inconvenience caused by this today, appreciate your patience and understanding, and most of all, thank you for supporting local!

Update from BEAM!
shared_text:
BEAM
August 12 at 2:01 PM ·

**OUTAGE ALERT**

An #UnplannedOutage occurred this morning after an ALDOT tractor mowing the right of way destroyed the main fiber cable pedestal providing service to the areas of Seale, Hurtsboro, and Hatchechubbee.

We understand a social media post and call was made by Russellcsd stating that the service could take up to two days to repair. We have reached back out to them as this will not be the case. Due to the severity of the damage, the restoration is taking much longer than normal, but we expect to have the schools restored by this afternoon and the remaining homes and businesses restored by tomorrow morning. Our dedicated technicians will work hard to get every customer back online as quickly as possible. *Please view updates via this post as we have them.*

Due to the outage, we are still taking calls however because of this outage, we have a unusually high call volume.

We apologize for the inconvenience, appreciate your patience, and understanding as we work to get services restored! As always, thank you for supporting local!

post_text:
Parents and Guardians,
As we begin the school year in a remote learning environment, we know that students will have different needs for support due to technology access. It is important that parents make teachers aware of their household’s technology needs during the first week of school.

Remote learning is intended to provide flexible access to instruction. Students may login to their Google Classroom at any time to access lessons and learning resources. Students may also work at their own pace to complete and submit assignments by the stated deadline. In the event that a live lesson is scheduled for student support, the teacher will communicate the specific time for that lesson based on information communicated by parents.

We appreciate your support, patience, and flexibility as we begin this year. Please reach out to your teachers and schools if you have any questions.

Thank you,
Mrs. Marceda Lewis and Dr. Adam Kilcrease, Directors of Curriculum and Instruction, RCSD

post_text: School Starts Tomorrow!
text: School Starts Tomorrow!

post_text:
Welcome Back, Warriors!

We are excited to welcome back all students, faculty, and staff in the Russell County School District for the 2020-2021 school year. All classes will begin remotely starting tomorrow, August 10, 2020, until September 10, 2020. During this time of uncertainty, our warrior family is committed to Rising Up for Education Excellence for every student. We will continue to support families that do not have technology devices or internet access. However, internet services can be accessed in various community locations. Please contact your child's school for assistance or additional information. Have a safe and great school year!!!

Dr. Brenda Coley, Superintendent of Russell County Schools

We will continue to support families that do not have technology devices or internet access. However, internet services can be accessed in various community locations. Please contact your child's school for assistance or additional information. Have a safe and great school year!!!

Dr. Brenda Coley, Superintendent of Russell County Schools

post_text:
The Alabama State Department of Education (ALSDE) has partnered with the University of Alabama to conduct a statewide school technology survey. The purpose of this survey is to build a statewide repository detailing Internet connectivity and Internet-enabled digital device availability to inform decision-makers as we expand remote learning capabilities and enhance high-quality instruction to students around the state.

Whether a student is attending school in a traditional classroom setting, virtually, or a blended version of traditional and virtual, it is important that we hear from parents across the state as the survey responses will impact our efforts to respond to ongoing changes relating to remote and blended learning options throughout our state. Please take a few moments to share and complete this statewide school technology survey. The deadline for completing the survey is Friday, July 31, 2020.

https://universityofalabama.az1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_9XKp7WfKVOLpZ3v

Russellcsd
June 4 at 10:50 AM ·

We are planning for the 2020-2021 School Year
Many of you have completed your child’s registration for the next school year and we are getting their homerooms and schedules complete for the new year.
Due to the COVID19 Stay at Home Orders, we will need to extend the registration deadline to July 13th. Registration is mandatory and students will need this completed in order for the homeroom assignment and schedules to be issued.
IF you have not received your child’s snapcode we have a link for you to submit a request on our website “Enroll” section located here - https://www.myrcsd.org/domain/48

⚠️Grade Level - Please note that the grade level in registration is for the school year just completed. Students were promoted to the proper grade for the 2020-2021 school year by the school. You do not have to make the change for the grade level inside the form.

post_text:
UPDATE: RCHS Graduation Ceremony
Due to the recent amendment to the social gathering guidelines released by Governor Kay Ivey, Russell County High School will be making changes to their graduation ceremony. The previous plan of a drive-in ceremony will be changed to a more traditional sit-down graduation ceremony. The graduation will still remain closed to the public and each graduate will be issued 4 tickets for guests to attend the ceremony. The 6-feet distancing guidelines will be maintained with reserved seating in the stands. Graduates will be seated on the field and will also maintain the 6-feet distancing guidelines. No one will be allowed past security checkpoints without a ticket. Seniors will be receiving more information in the near future about the procedures to follow.
Date: June 6th, 2020
Time: 9:00 a.m. EST
Location: Russell County High School Football Field

The new guidelines will enable us to consider adjusting the current plans for our up-coming RCHS Graduation Ceremony scheduled for Saturday, June 6, 2020. We will provide you with updated information as soon as possible. Thank you for your patience and support as we navigate through these times of uncertainty.

Thank you for your continued support and please continue to be safe.

Dear Parents and Guardians,

Learning Packet return and pickup is scheduled for this Thursday, April 23rd for grades 6-12 only.
Parents and or students should return previous- completed packets to the middle school or high school (depending on which school the student attends) on Thursday, April 23rd from 8-10 am and 4-6 pm. At this time, they will also receive a new packet that will be due back to the school on May 14th. This is only for students who are not participating in virtual instruction AND for grades 6-12 only. Students’ grades will be updated based on what is submitted.
Elementary students do not have to pick up another packet.

shared_text:
BEAM
March 17 at 11:57 AM ·

As a local business who cares deeply about our community and its citizens, we in partnership with the school systems are happy to ensure that every student and/or teacher who currently does not have broadband service is connected with internet for virtual learning. Along with the largest provider in the state, as a small local company, we equally have given the same accommodations they have offered in a time of need for this unforeseen outbreak to those less fortunate who did not have services. We are one of only three of the total 36 providers to have made accommodations in our state for those affected during the #CoronaVirus outbreak and proud to do so. We are mindful and will make appropriate accommodations as they come for all affected, existing and new customers combined. We simply want to ensure that all that need internet are connected! We continue to pray for those affected by #COVID19, with our great state of Alabama, and the nation.

March 15, 2020

This notification is in response to recent updates of Coronavirus, COVID-19. Russell County Schools will be closed beginning tomorrow, Monday, March 16th, and will reopen on Monday, April 6th. More information will be made available regarding student resources during school closure. Any further updates will be made available on our district website, social media page, and through messenger notifications. Safety is always our top priority. We appreciate your understanding and support.

Dr. Brenda Coley, Superintendent

post_text: This notification is in response to recent updates of Coronavirus, COVID-19. Russell County Schools will open Monday, March 16 through Wednesday, March 18, 2020. During this time, we will continue to take every measure to ensure the well-being of our students. Effective Thursday, March 19, 2020, all Russell County Schools will be closed until Monday, April 6, 2020, based on the order of the Governor. We will continue to provide information following the guidance from the U. S. Centers for Disease and Control(CDC), the Alabama Department of Public Health, and the Alabama State Department of Education. Curriculum activities, links to educational websites, and resources will be provided by teachers to keep students engaged during the closure. As always, we appreciate your understanding and support.

shared_text:
Jennifer Boswell Quillope‎Dixie Elementary
February 1 at 10:41 AM ·

Friday was a busy day in 3rd grade! Students presented their Cereal Box book reports and commercial! It was exciting to hear what books their peers read and how they created a cereal from it. Then they tried to persuade us to buy it with a 30 second commercial add. They even included a game on the back and a special prize inside in relation to their book. Students were also required to include characters, setting, and a summary of the book. It was a great time to review Author’s purpose as well. I am SO proud of all of their hard work!
Way to go 3rd graders!!!!

Mr. Ray graduated from Troy University where he was a member of the Sound of the South marching band. He pours into our students each day and prepares them for college, careers, and life. We are so lucky to have a band director and teacher in Mr. Ray!

Congratulations!!!!!
